entry.title: Avoid UB in PickleIterator::ReadBool
entry.content:
Not all bit patterns are valid bools. Instead, ReadBool should read into

a uint8_t first and then inspect the result. Additionally, always use

the memcpy path, rather than the pointer casting path. The pointer cast

is a strict aliasing violation (not that we enable that) and requires we

reason about alignment. I think alignment may actually be okay here, but

since every compiler understands memcpy, just do the straightforward and

safe thing.

entry.title: [SurfacePolish] Fix fake search box shiver-on-resize.
entry.content:
Previously on the Start Surface, when a vertical drag (with touch

starting from content) causes fake search box to resize, the screen

would vibrate vertically ("shiver"). This does not happen on the NTP.



This happens because the R.id.fake_search_box (fake search box

*container*) gets resized with R.id.search_box (fake search box). This

causes content below to shift upwards, which seems to confuse a drag in

progress. Interestingly, the problem is not universal (e.g., drag with

touch starting from R.id.sheet_container won't cause shiver).



A simple fix is to have R.id.fake_search_box maintain a constant size.

This has the additional benefit of having Start Surface more closely

match the NTP re. fake box resizing. In particular, the gap between

the fake search box and the tiles now grows during up-drag. Details:

* StartSurfaceCoordinator:

* updateFakeSearchBox(): Remove fakeSearchBoxContainerHeight param.

* updateFakeSearchBoxLayoutAndContainer(): Rename to

updateFakeSearchBoxHeight() and remove code to also change fake box

container height.

* StartSurfaceCoordinator.initializeOffsetChangedListener():

* Call StartSurfaceCoordinator.updateFakeSearchBoxContainer() to

fix R.id.fake_search_box height to |fakeHeightBeforeAnimation|.

* For Surface Polish: R.dimen.ntp_search_box_height_polish.

* For Original: R.dimen.ntp_search_box_height (no change).

* Do not change R.id.fake_search_box height thereafter.

* Introduce terms Phase 1/2/2A/2B/3 for fake search box resizing.

* Simplify logic for Surface Polish's resize special case (Phase 2A):

* Reorder by phase, and remove unneeded MathUtils.clamp().

entry.title: FuzzTest into Chromium
entry.content:
FuzzTest is a new fuzzing/property testing framework created elsewhere

in Google and open sourced. It increasingly subsumes the "centipede"

fuzzing engine which we already use in Chromium, but its main purpose is

to allow simple declarations of fuzzers within existing unit tests:



FUZZ_TEST(SomePreExistingFunction); // that's it, best case



This CL builds FuzzTest in Chromium and includes an example fuzzer of

how it can be used.



We are led to believe that the ease of adding FUZZ_TESTS has greatly

increased fuzzer production in other parts of Google, so we would like

to get the same benefits.



Tests built using FuzzTest can operate in a variety of modes, as

described in the BUILD.gn for fuzztest. One of those modes is

responsible for the most complex part of this change - a new gn

argument, "enable_fuzztest_fuzz". This is because unit tests built using

fuzztest can do a limited type of fuzzing even without any fuzzing

engines being enabled - this is a new capability for Chromium and

therefore it doesn't fit within any of our existing gn arguments, which

each pertain to a particular fuzzing engine (use_libfuzzer,

use_centipede, use_afl etc.) Specifically, without this gn argument,

a unit test can support:

./my_test # runs fuzzing for one second

With "enable_fuzztest_fuzz", additionally this option is supported:

./my_test --fuzz=0 # runs fuzzing indefinitely using coverage

# guidance



Adding a new gn argument is not ideal as it adds more permutations

to our build matrix which we need to test. This CL therefore enables

this option by default for sanitizer, Linux builds. At present it's

only enabled for non-component builds, which may not result in this

actually being built on any current builder, but there's a TODO to

fix this.

The solution is to use stop this distinction and treat every type

separately.

entry.title: HistorySyncBridge: Apply metadata deletions more consistently
entry.content:
When a history visit is deleted, any existing sync metadata should be

removed too, since it's not useful anymore.

Before this CL, that cleanup only happened if ShouldCommitRightNow()

was true at the time of deletion. That could in some cases lead to

metadata being left behind (e.g. when Sync was paused at the time).

So this CL relaxes the condition.



History Sync only keeps metadata around for entities pending commit,

so this situation rarely comes up. And the left-behind metadata wasn't

really harmful - at some future point, Sync might try to commit the

pending entity, not be able to retrieve its data, and give up. But

this did show up in metrics (see bug), so might as well fix it.

entry.title: Remove BAM::FillOrPreviewForm(Suggestion::BackendId)
entry.content:
The function retrieves the data model (profile or card) from the PDM

by the backend id and calls either FillOrPreviewProfileForm() or

FillOrPreviewCreditCardForm(). It only has a single non-test caller in

the external delegate.



This CL inlines the implementation there and migrates all callers to

either FillOrPreviewProfileForm() or FillOrPreviewCreditCardForm() (in

almost all cases, it's clear which one should be called).



This makes the external delegate slightly more complicated, but is

arguably the right change, since it simplifies the manager and our

filling API. (And it's what non-popup filling surfaces like TTF and

FastCheckout do).



The external delegate unit tests require some adaption: Currently, they

simply expect that FillOrPreviewForm() is called. These expectations are

changed to FillOrPreviewProfileForm() or FillOrPreviewCreditCardForm().

However, these functions are only called if the corresponding data model

is found in the PDM. Right now, the test setup doesn't take care of

that - and if fact doesn't even set backend ids properly.

To fix that, the tests are adapted by manually adding a profile (or

card) to the PDM and setting the backend ids of the suggestions

accordingly.

entry.title: Deprecate vector<v8::Local>, part 6
entry.content:
According to V8's public API documentation, local handles (i.e.,

objects of type v8::Local) "should never be allocated on the heap".

This disallows heap-allocated data structures containing instances of

v8::Local, like std::vector>. It is unfortunate

that the V8 API itself requires the usage of such data structures.



This CL continues the deprecation of such data structures. It replaces

such vectors with v8::LocalVector, recently introduced in V8 API,

which behave exactly the same with the exception that the V8 isolate

must be passed upon construction.



Most of the changes in this CL are trivial and are related to the

renderer.

entry.title: Revert "[Exo]Animation fix w.r.t RecreateLayers"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 9c093584851f4fe43f845cbb43663b0fae7a82ac.



Reason for revert: suspecting breaking crostini tests: b/307455741

Cq-Include-Trybots: luci.chrome.try:chromeos-eve-chrome



Original change's description:

> [Exo]Animation fix w.r.t RecreateLayers

>

> When an animation causes the `host_window` to `RecreateLayers`, the

> animation treats the new `host_window->layer` as if it's ready to be

> shown. Before the client has time to ack to the config event for that

> request, the `old_layer` prior to the cloning should be hosting the

> incoming wl_surface commits, i.e. it's the `commit_target_layer`.

>

> If incoming commits cause the surface hierarchy to change bounds, it

> should be changing bounds of the `commit_target_layer`, instead of the

> `host_window->layer`.

>

> This CL ensures that the bounds changes from the client goes to its

> `commit_target_layer`, and updates the `viz::SurfaceId` range for the

> `host_window->layer` s.t. fallback looks correct via stretching.

>

> Changes:

> 1) `Config`: stores an extra field `old_layer` to track the Layer

> prior to cloning.

> 2) `AllocateLocalSurfaceId`: `host_window`'s parent seq_number

> increments will be suppressed if they're originated from the client

> modifying the wayland surface hierarchy.

> 3) `GetCommitTargetLayer()`: returns the ui::Layer that can host

> client's surface commits. Due to animation cancelling destroying the

> old_layer with it, this may return nullptr.

> 4) `MaybeActivateSurface()`: for ShellSurface that has a config queue,

> it updates the surface range of `old_layer`s, and `host_window`'s

> layer, to be:

> [current_surface_id, max(layer_surface_id, current_surface_id)].

> And rely on stretching fallback surface when the deadline expires.

entry.title: Revert "pip-tuck: Add PipController"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 6856d1720708a6bfc7d5be2f42c565eeb9799705.



Reason for revert: Breaks MSAN, use of uninitialized value in the added code



Sample: https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/Linux%20ChromiumOS%20MSan%20Tests/39194/overview



Original change's description:

> pip-tuck: Add PipController

>

> Currently there is no general controller for Picture-in-Picture (PiP)

> windows. Having a dedicated controller for PiP windows would be useful

> because:

>

> 1. There are multiple parts of the code that can be simplified by

> introducing a controller that exists even when the PiP window does

> not exist, without having to rely on `WindowState` which should be

> reserved for more generic window functions. Examples include existing

> `CompleteDrag()` animations and tucking behavior for PiP which we are

> planning to implement.

>

> 2. A dedicated controller would allow for consolidation of the PiP

> window management controls code.

>

> This commit introduces the new class `PipController`, and also

> transplants `UpdatePipBounds()` from `WindowState` to the new

> `PipController`.

>

> This new `PipController` holds a reference to the window it is managing

> which can be obtained with `pip_window()`, and it is set with

> `SetPipWindow()` and unset with `UnsetPipWindow()`. It also holds an

> observer that observes this window when it is set.

>

> Bug: b/305611254

> Test: ash_unittests PipControllerTest*

>
